<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2005D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Find the speed of a particle with the given position function
<me>
\vr(t) = 5 \sqrt{2}\,t\,\hi + e^{5t}\,\hj - e^{-5t}\,\hk
</me>
Select the correct answer:
<ol label="a">
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = \big(e^{5t} + e^{-5t}\big)</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = \sqrt{10 + 5e^{t} + 5e^{-t}}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = \sqrt{10 + e^{10t} + e^{-10t}}</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = 5\big(e^{5t} + e^{-5t}\big)</m>
</li>
<li>
<m>|\vv(t)| = 5\big(e^t + e^{-t}\big)</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Just compute <m>|\vv(t)|</m>. Note that <m>\big(e^{at}+e^{-at}\big)^2
=e^{2at} + 2 + e^{-2at}</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(d)
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We have
<me>
\vv(t) = \vr'(t)
      = 5 \sqrt{2}\,\hi + 5e^{5t}\,\hj +5 e^{-5t}\,\hk
</me>
and hence
<me>
|\vv(t)| = |\vr'(t)|
         = 5 \big|\sqrt{2}\,\hi + e^{5t}\,\hj + e^{-5t}\,\hk\big|
         = 5\sqrt{2+ e^{10t}+ e^{-10t}}
</me>
Since <m>2+ e^{10t}+ e^{-10t} = \big(e^{5t}+e^{-5t}\big)^2</m>, that's (d).
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the velocity, speed and acceleration at time <m>t</m> of
the particle whose position is
<me>
\vr(t)= a \cos t\,\hi+a\sin t\,\hj+ct\,\hk
</me>
Describe the path of the particle.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
To figure out what the path looks like, first concentrate on the <m>x</m>- and
<m>y</m>-coordinates.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\text{velocity}=-a \sin t\,\hi+a\cos t\,\hj+c\,\hk</m></p><p>
<m>\text{speed}= \sqrt{a^2+c^2}</m></p><p>
<m>\text{acceleration}=-a \cos t\,\hi-a\sin t\,\hj</m>
</p>

<p>The path is a helix with radius <m>a</m> and with each turn having height <m>2\pi c</m>.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
We are told that
<me>
\vr(t)= a \cos t\,\hi+a\sin t\,\hj+ct\,\hk
</me>
So, by definition,
<md>
<mrow>
\text{velocity}&amp;= \vv(t)= \vr'(t)=-a \sin t\,\hi+a\cos t\,\hj+c\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\text{speed}&amp;=\diff{s}{t}(t) = |\vr'(t)| = \sqrt{a^2+c^2}
</mrow><mrow>
\text{acceleration}&amp;=\va(t)= \vr''(t)=-a \cos t\,\hi-a\sin t\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
As <m>t</m> runs over an interval of length <m>2\pi</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> traces
out a circle of radius <m>a</m> and <m>z</m> increases by <m>2\pi c</m>.
The path is a helix with radius <m>a</m> and with each turn having height <m>2\pi c</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2013D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p><ol label="a">
<li>
Let
<me>
\vr(t) = \left(t^2 , 3, \tfrac{1}{3} t^3 \right)
</me>
Find the unit tangent vector to this parametrized curve at <m>t = 1</m>,
pointing in the direction of increasing <m>t</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the arc length of the curve from (a) between the points <m>(0, 3, 0)</m>
and <m>(1, 3, -\frac{1}{3})</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Review ยง<xref ref="sec_CurveCompendium"/>.
The arc length should be positive.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\hat\vT(1) = \frac{(2,0,1)}{\sqrt{5}}</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{1}{3}\big[5^{3/2}-8\big]</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a)
Since <m>\vr'(t) = (2t,0,t^2)</m>, the specified unit tangent at <m>t=1</m> is
<me>
\hat\vT(1) = \frac{(2,0,1)}{\sqrt{5}}
</me>
</p>

<p> (b)
We are to find the arc length between <m>\vr(0)</m> and <m>\vr(-1)</m>.
As <m>\diff{s}{t}=\sqrt{4t^2+t^4}</m>, the
<md>
<mrow>
\text{arc length} &amp;= \int_{-1}^0 \sqrt{4t^2+t^4}\ \dee{t}
</mrow>
</md>
The integrand is even, so
<md>
<mrow>
\text{arc length} &amp;= \int_0^1 \sqrt{4t^2+t^4}\ \dee{t}
=\int_0^1 t\sqrt{4+t^2}\ \dee{t}
=\Big[\tfrac{1}{3}{(4+t^2)}^{3/2}\Big]_0^1
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\tfrac{1}{3}\big[5^{3/2}-8\big]
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="prob_s1_1_lemma113">
<statement><p>
Using Lemma<nbsp/><xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/>,
find the arclength of <m>\vr(t)=\left(t,\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}t^2,t^3\right)</m>
from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=1</m>.
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
From Lemma<nbsp/><xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/>, we know
the arclength from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=1</m> will be
<me>
\int_{0}^1\left| \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|\dee t</me>
</p>

<p>The notation looks a little confusing at first, but we can break it down piece by piece: <m>\diff{\vr}{t}(t)</m> is a vector, whose components are functions of <m>t</m>. If we take its magnitude, we'll get one big function of <m>t</m>. That function is what we integrate. Before integrating it, however, we should simplify as much as possible.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
2
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
By Lemma<nbsp/><xref ref="lem_CVtanArclen"/>
the arclength of <m>\vr(t)</m> from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=1</m> is
<m>\int_{0}^1\left| \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|\dee t</m>. We'll calculate this in a few pieces to make the steps clearer.
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;=\left(t,\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}t^2,t^3\right)
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{\vr}{t}(t)&amp;=\left(1,\sqrt{6}t,3t^2\right)
</mrow><mrow>
\left|\diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|&amp;=\sqrt{1^2+(\sqrt{6}t)^2+(3t^2)^2}=\sqrt{1+6t^2+9t^4}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\sqrt{(3t^2+1)^2}=3t^2+1
</mrow><mrow>
\int_{0}^1\left| \diff{\vr}{t}(t)\right|\dee t&amp;=\int_0^1\left(3t^2+1 \right)\dee t=2
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the length of the parametric curve
<me>
x=a\cos t\sin t\qquad
y=a\sin^2 t\qquad
z=bt
</me>
between <m>t=0</m> and <m>t=T \gt 0</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>\text{length}=\sqrt{a^2+b^2}\,T</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Since
<md>
<mrow>
x'(t)&amp;=a\big[\cos^2 t-\sin^2 t\big]=a\cos 2t
</mrow><mrow>
y'(t)&amp;=2a\sin t\cos t=a\sin 2t
</mrow><mrow>
z'(t)&amp;=b
</mrow>
</md>
we have
<me>
\diff{s}{t}(t)
=\sqrt{x'(t)^2+y'(t)^2+z'(t)^2}=\sqrt{a^2+b^2}
</me>
As the speed <m>\diff{s}{t}(t)</m> is constant, the length is just
<m>\diff{s}{t}\,T=\sqrt{a^2+b^2}\,T</m>.
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
A particle's position at time <m>t</m> is given by <m>\vr(t)=(t+\sin t, \cos t)</m>
<fn>The particle traces out a cycloid <mdash/> see Question<nbsp/><xref ref="prob_s1_1_cycloid"/></fn>. What is the magnitude of the acceleration of the particle at time <m>t</m>?
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
<m>\vr(t)</m> is the position of the particle, so its acceleration is <m>r''(t)</m>.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
1
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Since <m>\vr(t)</m> is the position of the particle,  its acceleration is <m>r''(t)</m>.
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;=(t+\sin t, \cos t)
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t)&amp;=(1+\cos t,-\sin t)
</mrow><mrow>
\vr''(t)&amp;=(-\sin t,-\cos t)
</mrow><mrow>
|\vr''(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{\sin^2t+\cos^2t}=1
</mrow>
</md>
The magnitude of acceleration is constant, but its <em>direction</em> is changing, since <m>\vr''(t)</m> is a vector with changing direction.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2011D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
A curve in <m>\bbbr^3</m> is given by the vector equation
<m>\vr(t) = \left(2t \cos t, 2t \sin t,\frac{t^3}{3}\right)</m>
</p>

<p><ol label="a">
<li>
Find the length of the curve between <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 2</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the parametric equations of the tangent line to the curve at <m>t = \pi</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Review ยง<xref ref="sec_CurveCompendium"/>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\frac{20}{3}</m></p><p>
(b) <m>x(t) = -2\pi -2t,\
     y(t) =  -2\pi t,\
     z(t) = \frac{\pi^3}{3} + \pi^2 t</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a) The speed is
<md>
<mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)
=\big|\vr'(t)\big| &amp; = \left|\left(2\cos t - 2t\sin t\,,\,
                                  2\sin t + 2t \cos t\,,\,
                                  t^2\right)\right|
</mrow><mrow>
                  &amp;=\sqrt{\big(2\cos t - 2t\sin t\big)^2
                         +\big(2\sin t + 2t \cos t\big)^2
                         +t^4}
</mrow><mrow>
                 &amp;= \sqrt{4+ 4t^2 +t^4}
</mrow><mrow>
                 &amp;= 2+t^2
</mrow>
</md>
so the length of the curve is
<md>
<mrow>
\text{length }
&amp;=\int_0^2 \diff{s}{t}\,\dee{t}
  =\int_0^2 (2+t^2)\,\dee{t}
  = \left[2t +\frac{t^3}{3}\right]_0^2
  =\frac{20}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p> (b)
A tangent vector to the curve at
<m>\vr(\pi)=\big(-2\pi\,,\, 0\,,\, \frac{\pi^3}{3}\big)</m> is
<me>
\vr'(\pi) = \left(2\cos\pi - 2\pi\sin\pi\,,\,
                                  2\sin\pi + 2\pi \cos\pi\,,\,
                                  \pi^2\right)
 = (-2\,,\,-2\pi\,,\,\pi^2)
</me>
So parametric equations for the tangent line at <m>\vr(\pi)</m> are
<md>
<mrow>
x(t) &amp;= -2\pi -2t
</mrow><mrow>
y(t) &amp;=  -2\pi t
</mrow><mrow>
z(t) &amp;= \frac{\pi^3}{3} + \pi^2 t
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2010D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vr(t) = \big(3 \cos t, 3 \sin t, 4t\big)</m> be the position vector
of a particle as a function of time <m>t \ge 0</m>.
<ol label="a">
<li>
Find the velocity of the particle as a function of time <m>t</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the arclength of its path between <m>t = 1</m> and <m>t = 2</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Review ยง<xref ref="sec_curve_derivs"/>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\vr'(t) = \big(-3 \sin t, 3 \cos t, 4\big)</m></p><p>
(b) 5
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a) As <m>\vr(t) = \big(3 \cos t, 3 \sin t, 4t\big)</m>,
the velocity of the particle is
<me>
\vr'(t) = \big(-3 \sin t, 3 \cos t, 4\big)
</me>
</p>

<p> (b) As <m>\diff{s}{t}</m>, the rate of change of arc length per unit time,
is
<me>
\diff{s}{t}(t) = |\vr'(t)| = \big|\big(-3 \sin t, 3 \cos t, 4\big)\big|
  =5
</me>
the arclength of its path between <m>t = 1</m> and <m>t = 2</m> is
