<exercise>
<statement><p>
The plane <m>\ z=2x+3y\ </m> intersects the cylinder
<m>\ x^2+y^2=9\ </m> in an ellipse.
<ol label="a">
<li>
Find a parametrization of the ellipse.
</li>
<li>
Express the circumference of this ellipse as an integral.
You need not evaluate the integral<fn>The indefinite integral involved is one of a class of integrals called elliptic integrals because of their connections to arc lengths of ellipses. In general, elliptic integrals cannot be expressed in terms of elementary functions. You can easily find discussions of elliptic integrals using your favourite search engine.</fn>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
(a) First parametrize <m>x^2+y^2=9</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>x(\theta)=3\cos\theta,\
y(\theta)=3\sin\theta,\
z(\theta)=6\cos\theta+9\sin\theta,\
0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m>
</p>

<p>(b) <m>s=\int_0^{2\pi} \sqrt{45+45\cos^2\theta-108\sin\theta\cos\theta}\,d\theta</m>
</p>

</answer>

<solution><p> (a)
We can parametrize the circle  <m>\ x^2+y^2=9\ </m> as
<m>x(\theta)=3\cos\theta</m>, <m>y(\theta)=3\sin\theta</m> with
<m>\theta</m> running from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>. As <m>z=2x+3y</m>, the
ellipse can be parametrized by
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;x(\theta)=3\cos\theta,\
y(\theta)=3\sin\theta,\
z(\theta)=2x(\theta)+3 y(\theta)
        =6\cos\theta+9\sin\theta
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;
0\le\theta\le 2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b)
As
<md>
<mrow>
\diff{s}{\theta}
 &amp;=\sqrt{x'(\theta)^2+y'(\theta)^2+z'(\theta)^2}
</mrow><mrow>
 &amp;=\sqrt{9\sin^2\theta+9\cos^2\theta+36\sin^2\theta
        +81\cos^2\theta-108\sin\theta\cos\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\sqrt{45+45\cos^2\theta-108\sin\theta\cos\theta}
</mrow>
</md>
the circumference is
<me>
s=\int_0^{2\pi} \sqrt{45+45\cos^2\theta-108\sin\theta\cos\theta}\,\dee{\theta}
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
	Consider the curve
	<me>
	\vr(t) = \frac{1}{3}\cos^3 t\,\hi +\frac{1}{3} \sin^3 t\,\hj + \sin^3 t\,\hk
	</me>
	<ol label="a">
<li>
		Compute the arc length of the curve from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
</li>
<li>
		Compute the arc length of the curve from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \pi</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
	If you got the answer <m>0</m> in part (b), you dropped some absolute value signs.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
	(a) <m>\frac{1}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)</m></p><p>
	(b) <m>\frac{2}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a)
	As
	<md>
<mrow>
	\vr'(t) &amp; = -\sin t\cos^2 t\,\hi + \sin^2 t\cos t\,\hi + 3\sin^2 t\cos t\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
 	&amp;= \sin t\cos t\big(-\cos t\,\hi +\sin t\,\hj +3\sin t\,\hk\big)
</mrow><mrow>
	\diff{s}{t}(t) &amp; = |\sin t\cos t|\sqrt{\cos^2 t + \sin ^2 t + 9\sin^2 t}
	= |\sin t\cos t|\sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}
	</mrow>
</md>
	the arclength from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \frac{\pi}{2}</m> is
	<md>
<mrow>
	&amp;\int_0^{\pi/2} \diff{s}{t}(t)\,\dee{t}
	=\int_0^{\pi/2} \sin t\cos t \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;\hskip0.5in=\frac{1}{18}\int_1^{10} \sqrt{u}\ \dee{u} \qquad
	\text{with } u = 1+ 9\sin^2 t,\ \dee{u}  = 18\sin t\cos t\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;\hskip0.5in=\frac{1}{18}\Big[\frac{2}{3}u^{3/2}\Big]_1^{10}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;\hskip0.5in=\frac{1}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)
	</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>	(b) The arclength from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \pi</m> is
	<md>
<mrow>
	\int_0^{\pi} \diff{s}{t}(t)\,\dee{t}
	&amp;=\int_0^{\pi} |\sin t\cos t| \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
         </mrow><mrow>
	&amp;\hskip1in\text{Don't forget the absolute value signs!}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;=2\int_0^{\pi/2} |\sin t\cos t| \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
	&amp;= 2\int_0^{\pi/2} \sin t\cos t \sqrt{1+ 9\sin^2 t}\,\dee{t}
	</mrow>
</md>
	since the integrand is invariant under <m>t\rightarrow\pi-t</m>. So the arc length
	from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = \pi</m> is just twice the arc length from part (a), namely <m>\frac{2}{27}\big(10\sqrt{10}-1\big)</m>.
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vr(t)=\big(\frac{1}{3}t^3,\frac{1}{2}t^2,\frac{1}{2}t\big)</m>,
<m>t\ge 0</m>. Compute <m>s(t</m>), the arclength of the curve at time
<m>t</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>s(t)=\frac{t^3}{3} +\frac{t}{2}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Since
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t)&amp;= \frac{t^3}{3}\,\hi + \frac{t^2}{2}\,\hj +  \frac{t}{2}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t)&amp;= t^2\,\hi + t\,\hj + \frac{1}{2}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t}(t)=|\vr'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{t^4+t^2+\frac{1}{4}}
=\sqrt{\Big(t^2+\frac{1}{2}\Big)^2}=t^2+\frac{1}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
the length of the curve is
<md>
<mrow>
s(t)=\int_0^t \diff{s}{t}(u)\,\dee{u}
=\int_0^t \Big(u^2+\frac{1}{2}\Big)\,\dee{u}
=\frac{t^3}{3} +\frac{t}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2011A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Find the arc length of the curve
<m>\vr(t) = \big(t^m\,,\, t^m\,,\, t^{3m/2}\big)</m> for <m>0 \le a \le t \le b</m>,
and where <m>m  \gt  0</m>.
Express your result in terms of <m>m</m>, <m>a</m>, and <m>b</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The integral you get can be evaluated with
a simple substitution. You may want to factor the integrand first.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{8}{27}\Big[\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m\Big)^{3/2}
                   -\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m\Big)^{3/2}\Big]</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Since
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t) &amp; = t^m\,\hi + t^m\,\hj + t^{3m/2}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t) &amp;= mt^{m-1}\,\hi + mt^{m-1}\,\hj +\frac{3m}{2}t^{3m/2-1}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{t} = |\vr'(t)| &amp; = \sqrt{ 2m^2 t^{2m-2} +\frac{9m^2}{4} t^{3m-2} }
= mt^{m-1}\sqrt{2 + \frac{9}{4}t^m }
</mrow>
</md>
the arc length is
<md>
<mrow>
\int_a^b \diff{s}{t}(t)\,\dee{t}
&amp;=\int_a^b mt^{m-1}\sqrt{2 + \frac{9}{4}t^m }\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{4}{9}\int_{2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m}^{2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m}\sqrt{u}\,\dee{u}
\qquad\text{with } u = 2 + \frac{9}{4}t^m,\ \dee{u} = \frac{9m}{4}t^{m-1}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{4}{9}\Big[\frac{2}{3}u^{3/2}\Big]_{2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m}
                                         ^{2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{8}{27}\Big[\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}b^m\Big)^{3/2}
                   -\Big(2 + \frac{9}{4}a^m\Big)^{3/2}\Big]
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
 Let <m>C</m> be the part of the curve of intersection of the
parabolic cylinder <m>x = y^2</m> and the hyperbolic  paraboloid <m>3z = 2xy</m>
with <m>y\ge 0</m>.
<ol label="a">
<li>
   Write a vector parametric equation for <m>C</m> using <m>x</m> as the parameter.
</li>
<li>
   Find the length of the part of <m>C</m> between the origin and
   the point <m>(9, 3, 18)</m>.
</li>
<li>
   A particle moves along <m>C</m> in the direction for which <m>x</m> is
   increasing.  If the particle  moves with constant speed 9, find
   its velocity vector when it is at  the point <m>(1, 1, \frac{2}{3})</m>.
</li>
<li>
   Find the acceleration vector of the particle of part (c)
   when it is at  the point <m>(1, 1, \frac{2}{3})</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
(b) <m>\frac{1}{4x}+1+x</m> is a perfect square.
</p>

<p>(c), (d) Let
<ul>
<li>
  <m>\vr(x)</m> be the position of the particle when its first coordinate is <m>x</m>,
</li>
<li>
 <m>\vR(t)</m> be the position of the particle at time <m>t</m>, and
</li>
<li>
  <m>x(t)</m> be the <m>x</m>--coordinate of the particle at time <m>t</m>.
</li>
</ul>
Then <m>\vR(t) = \vr\big(x(t)\big)</m>. We are told <m>|\vR'(t)|=9</m> for all <m>t</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\vr(x)=x\,\hi+\sqrt{x}\,\hj+\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}\,\hk</m></p><p>
(b) <m>21</m></p><p>
(c) <m>6\,\hi+3\,\hj+6\,\hk</m></p><p>
(d) <m>-6\,\hi-12\,\hj+12\,\hk</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a)
Since <m>y=\sqrt{x}</m> and <m>z=\frac{2}{3}xy=\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(x)&amp;=x\,\hi+\sqrt{x}\,\hj+\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
For the remaining parts of this problem we will also need
<md>
<mrow>
\vr'(x)&amp;=\hi+\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}\,\hj+\sqrt{x}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vr''(x)&amp;=-\frac{1}{4x^{3/2}}\,\hj+\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}\,\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{x}=|\vr'(x)|
&amp;=\sqrt{1+\frac{1}{4x}+x}
=\sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}+\sqrt{x}\right)^2}
=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}+\sqrt{x}
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{s}{x}(1)&amp;=\frac{3}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b)
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \ ds
&amp;=\int_0^9 \diff{s}{x}\ \dee{x}
=\int_0^9 \left(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}+\sqrt{x}\right)\ \dee{x}
=\left[\sqrt{x}+\frac{2}{3}x^{3/2}\right]_0^9
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3+18
=21
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(c)
Denote by
<ul>
<li>
  <m>\vr(x)</m> the position of the particle when its first coordinate is <m>x</m>,
</li>
<li>
 <m>\vR(t)</m> the position of the particle at time <m>t</m>,
</li>
<li>
  <m>x(t)</m> the <m>x</m>--coordinate of the particle at time <m>t</m>, and
</li>
<li>
  <m>s(x)</m> the arc length of the curve from the origin to <m>\vr(x)</m>.
</li>
</ul>
We are told that <m>|\vR'(t)|=9</m> for all <m>t</m>.
So
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\vR(t)=\vr\big(x(t)\big)\implies
\vR'(t)=\vr'\big(x(t)\big)\diff{x}{t}(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in\implies
9=|\vR'(t)|=\diff{s}{x}\big(x(t)\big) \diff{x}{t}(t)
=\left(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x(t)}}+\sqrt{x(t)}\right)\diff{x}{t}(t)
</mrow>
</md>
In particular, if the particle is at <m>(1,1,\frac{2}{3})</m> at time <m>0</m>, then <m>x(0)=1</m>
and
<me>
9=\left(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{1}}+\sqrt{1}\right)\diff{x}{t}(0)
\implies \diff{x}{t}(0)=6
</me>
so that
<me>
\vR'(0)=\vr'(1)\diff{x}{t}(0)
=\left(\hi+\frac{1}{2}\,\hj+\hk\right)6
=\ 6\,\hi+3\,\hj+6\,\hk
</me>
</p>

<p>(d)
By the product and chain rules,
<me>
\vR'(t)=\vr'\big(x(t)\big)\diff{x}{t}(t)\implies
\vR''(t)=\vr''\big(x(t)\big)\left(\diff{x}{t}(t)\right)^2
+\vr'\big(x(t)\big)\difftwo{x}{t}(t)
</me>
We saw in part (c) that
<m>9=|\vR'(t)|=\Big(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x(t)}}+\sqrt{x(t)}\Big)\diff{x}{t}(t)</m>
so that
<me>
\diff{x}{t}(t)=9\left(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x(t)}}+\sqrt{x(t)}\right)^{-1}
</me>
Differentiating that gives
<me>
\frac{d^2x}{dt^2}(t)=-9\left(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x(t)}}+\sqrt{x(t)}\right)^{-2}
\left(-\frac{1}{4x(t)^{3/2}}+\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x(t)}}\right)\diff{x}{t}(t)
</me>
In particular, when <m>t=0</m>, <m>x(0)=1</m> and <m>\diff{x}{t}(0)=6</m>
<me>
\difftwo{x}{t}(0)=-9\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^{-2}
\left(\frac{1}{4}\right)6=-6
</me>
so
<md>
<mrow>
\vR''(0)&amp;=\vr''(1)\ \big(6\big)^2+\vr'(1)\big(-6\big)
=36\left(-\frac{1}{4}\,\hj+\frac{1}{2}\,\hk\right)
-6\left(\hi+\frac{1}{2}\,\hj+\hk\right)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-6\,\hi-12\,\hj+12\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
If a particle has constant mass <m>m</m>, position <m>\vr</m>, and is moving with velocity <m>\vv</m>, then its angular momentum is <m>\vL=m(\vr\times\vv)</m>.
</p>

<p>For a particle with mass <m>m=1</m> and position function <m>\vr=(\sin t, \cos t, t)</m>, find <m>\left|\diff{\vL}{t} \right|</m>.
</p>

</statement>
<hint><p>
Given the position of a particle, you can find its velocity.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
<m>|t|</m>
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Given the position of the particle, we can find its velocity:
<me>
\vv(t)=\vr'(t)=(\cos t, -\sin t , 1)</me>
</p>

<p>Applying the given formula,
<me>
\vL(t)=\vr \times \vv=(\sin t , \cos t , t) \times (\cos t, -\sin t , 1).</me>
</p>

<p><ul>
<li>[<alert>Solution 1:</alert>]
We can first compute the cross product, then differentiate:
<md>
<mrow>
\vL(t)&amp; = (\cos t + t\sin t)\hi + (t\cos t - \sin t)\hj-\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vL'(t)&amp;=t\cos t\,\hi -t\sin t\, \hj
</mrow><mrow>
|\vL'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{t^2(\sin^2 t + \cos^2 t)}=\sqrt{t^2}=|t|
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
<li>[<alert>Solution 2:</alert>]
Using the product rule:
<md>
<mrow>
\vL'(t)&amp;=\vr'(t)\times \vv(t) + \vr(t) \times \vv'(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\underbrace{\vr'(t)\times \vr'(t)}_{0} + \vr(t) \times \vv'(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= (\sin t ,\cos t,t)\times(-\sin t , -\cos t, 0)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=t\cos t\,\hi-t\sin t\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
|\vL'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{t^2\cos^2 t + t^2\sin t^2  }=|t|
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
</ul>
</p></solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

